"1292","1316":"1316","1304":"1304","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1301":"1301","1344":"1344","1278":"1278","about 1304":"circa 1304","Oct 1315":"oktober 1315","about 1302":"circa 1302","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Morehouse, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wakefield St Mary, Yorkshire, England":"Wakefield St Mary, Yorkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Moorhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1270–1316":"1270–1316","1278–1315":"1278–1315","1292–Female":"1292–Deceased","1301–1344":"1301–1344","1302–Male":"1302–Deceased","1304–Male":"1304–Deceased","1240–1270":"1240–1270","1242–1293":"1242–1293","about 1292":"about 1292","1242":"1242","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1293":"1293","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","1316":"1316","1304":"1304","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1301":"1301","1344":"1344","1278":"1278","about 1304":"about 1304","Oct 1315":"October 1315","about 1302":"about 1302","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Morehouse, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Wakefield St Mary, Yorkshire, England":"Wakefield St Mary, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Moorhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan DeStainton was born in 1270, her father, John de Stainton, was 30 and her mother, Joan de Wollay, was 28. She married Thomas de Dromsfield in 1295, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1316, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1270–1316":"1270–1316","1278–1315":"1278–1315","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","1301–1344":"1301–1344","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1240–1270":"1240–1270","1242–1293":"1242–1293","about 1292":"umbes 1292","1242":"1242","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1293":"1293","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","1316":"1316","1304":"1304","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1301":"1301","1344":"1344","1278":"1278","about 1304":"umbes 1304","Oct 1315":"oktoober 1315","about 1302":"umbes 1302","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Morehouse, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wakefield St Mary, Y